<<imports>>=
from pathlib import Path
import shlex
import subprocess
import venv
@

\section{Creating the environment}

Environment creation is intentionally idempotent.  Once [[path/bin/python]]
exists, callers already have a usable virtual environment and should keep any
packages currently installed inside it.  That makes [[mentipy init]] safe to
rerun: the command can detect whether it is provisioning or merely refreshing
the package installation.

<<functions>>=
def create_venv(path: Path) -> bool:
    """Create a virtual environment at ``path`` if needed.

    Return ``True`` when a new environment was created, else ``False``.
    """

    if (path / "bin" / "python").exists():
        return False

    venv.EnvBuilder(with_pip=True).create(path)
    return True
@

The creation test uses a real virtual environment because the contract is about
filesystem side effects and idempotence, not just about calling into
[[venv.EnvBuilder]].

<<test functions>>=
def test_create_venv_creates_once_and_then_stays_idempotent(tmp_path):
    path = tmp_path / ".venv"

    assert create_venv(path) is True
    assert (path / "bin" / "python").exists()
    assert create_venv(path) is False
@

\section{Installing mentipy into the environment}

Package installation goes through the environment's own interpreter rather than
through a separate [[pip]] executable.  That keeps the target interpreter
unambiguous and works even when shell activation has not happened yet.

<<functions>>=
def install_package(venv_path: Path, package: str = "mentipy") -> None:
    """Install or upgrade ``package`` inside ``venv_path``."""

    subprocess.run(
        [
            str(venv_path / "bin" / "python"),
            "-m",
            "pip",
            "install",
            "--upgrade",
            package,
        ],
        check=True,
    )
@

The installation helper is a thin subprocess wrapper, so the regression test
only needs to pin the exact command shape and the [[check=True]] contract.

<<test functions>>=
def test_install_package_uses_the_venv_python(monkeypatch, tmp_path):
    calls = []

    def fake_run(command, check):
        calls.append((command, check))

    monkeypatch.setattr("mentipy.venv.subprocess.run", fake_run)

    install_package(tmp_path / ".venv", package="mentipy")

    assert calls == [
        (
            [
                str(tmp_path / ".venv" / "bin" / "python"),
                "-m",
                "pip",
                "install",
                "--upgrade",
                "mentipy",
            ],
            True,
        )
    ]
@

\section{Generating activation commands}

The activation output is a shell snippet rather than a shell script file.  That
keeps [[mentipy activate]] easy to compose with [[eval $(mentipy activate)]]
and avoids assuming that users want the standard activation script's prompt
customisation.  We emit absolute paths and POSIX shell quoting so the result is
safe even when the virtual environment lives under a directory with spaces.

<<functions>>=
def activation_script(venv_path: Path) -> str:
    """Return POSIX shell commands that activate ``venv_path``."""

    absolute = shlex.quote(str(venv_path.resolve()))
    return "\n".join(
        (
            f"export VIRTUAL_ENV={absolute}",
            'export PATH="$VIRTUAL_ENV/bin:$PATH"',
            "unset PYTHONHOME",
            "hash -r 2>/dev/null || true",
        )
    )
@

The activation helper should stay byte-for-byte predictable because the CLI
prints it directly for shell evaluation.

<<test functions>>=
def test_activation_script_uses_an_absolute_single_quoted_path(tmp_path):
    path = tmp_path / "course env"

    assert activation_script(path) == "\n".join(
        (
            f"export VIRTUAL_ENV='{path.resolve()}'",
            'export PATH="$VIRTUAL_ENV/bin:$PATH"',
            "unset PYTHONHOME",
            "hash -r 2>/dev/null || true",
        )
    )
@

